## Interpretation

Working backward clarifies the design rule: the closest natural match is not an early `q - 1` form. It is the late direct-q arm after the root-square-minus-one cancellation, because that leaves the cancellation operand phase visible relative to `ulp(f)`.

Every early-operand principle tested is an anti-conformer for the half grid: it globally cleans the lattice but locks to same phase. That makes it useful for cleanup, not for increasing comb density.

The next productive move is a constrained q-phase law search on the late-q arm, especially Schwarzschild `f_binade_-1`, where the best natural principle already reaches `16 / 22` half-grid hits. More equivalent `q - 1 == -f` rewrites are unlikely to help.

